{"cursor":"91384","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":" is a natural fusion reactor.]] 'Fusion power' is the power generated by nuclear\n fusion processes. In fusion reactions two light atomic nuclei fuse together to\n form a heavier nucleus (in contrast with fission power). In doing so they\n release a comparatively large amount of energy arising from the binding energy\n due to the strong nuclear force which is manifested as an increase in\n temperature of the reactants. Fusion power is a primary area of research in\n plasma physics.\n\nThe term is commonly used to refer to potential commercial production of net\nusable power from a fusion source, similar to the usage of the term \"steam\npower.\" The leading designs for controlled fusion research use magnetic\n(tokamak design) or inertial (laser) confinement of a plasma, with heat from\nthe fusion reactions used to operate a steam turbine which in turn drives\nelectrical generators, similar to the process used in fossil fuel and nuclear\nfission power stations.\n\n, the largest experiment by means of magnetic confinement has been the Joint\nEuropean Torus (JET). In 1997, JET produced a peak of of fusion power (65% of\ninput power), with fusion power of over sustained for over 0.5 sec. Its\nsuccessor, the International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor (ITER), was\nofficially announced as part of a seven-party consortium (six countries and the\nEU). [http://www.pppl.gov/polImage.cfm?doc_Id=603&size_code=Doc\nITER and the Promise of Fusion Energy]. ITER is designed to produce ten\ntimes more fusion power than the power put into the plasma. ITER is currently\nunder construction in Cadarache, France.\n\nInertial (laser) confinement, which was for a time seen as more difficult or\ninfeasible, has generally seen less development effort than magnetic approaches.\nHowever, this approach made a comeback following further innovations, and is\nbeing developed at both the United States National Ignition Facility, the French\nLaser MÃ©gajoule as well as the planned European Union High Power laser Energy\nResearch (HiPER) facility. NIF reached initial operational status in 2010 and\nhas been in the process of increasing the power and energy of its \"shots\".\nFusion ignition tests are to follow.\n\nFusion powered electricity generation was initially believed to be readily\nachievable, as fission power had been. However, the extreme requirements for\ncontinuous reactions and plasma containment led to projections being extended by\nseveral decades. In 2010, more than 60 years after the first attempts,\ncommercial power production was still believed to be unlikely before 2050. - Projected fusion power timeline\n","linknr":1459,"url":"Fusion_power","recorded":1362512658,"links":111,"instances":["disambiguation","tokamak","fusion","fusion_reactor","tokamak","physics","plasma_physics","physics","fusion_reactor","plasma_physics"],"pdf":["http://www.iop.org/Jet/fulltext/JETP99028.pdf","http://www.iop.org/Jet/fulltext/JETP99028.pdf","http://www.askmar.com/ConferenceNotes/2006-9%20IAC%20Paper.pdf","http://iopscience.iop.org/1742-6596/112/4/042084/pdf/jpconf8_112_042084.pdf","http://arxiv.org/ftp/arxiv/papers/0710/0710.3149.pdf","http://web.archive.org/web/20040506065141/http://www.worldenergy.org/wec-geis/publications/default/tech_papers/18th_Congress/downloads/ds/ds6/ds6_5.pdf","http://www.worldenergy.org/wec-geis/publications/default/tech_papers/18th_Congress/downloads/ds/ds6/ds6_5.pdf","http://web.archive.org/web/20040506065141/http://www.worldenergy.org/wec-geis/publications/default/tech_papers/18th_Congress/downloads/ds/ds6/ds6_5.pdf","http://www.agci.org/dB/PDFs/03S2_MMauel_SafeFusion%3F.pdf","http://ec.europa.eu/research/fp6/pdf/fp6-in-brief_en.pdf","http://ec.europa.eu/research/fp6/pdf/fp6-in-brief_en.pdf","http://www.agci.org/dB/PDFs/03S2_MMauel_SafeFusion%3F.pdf","http://www.agci.org/dB/PDFs/03S2_MMauel_SafeFusion%3F.pdf","http://www.plasmafocus.net/IPFS/2010%20Papers/LSma